Wash and dry produce. Peel and mince @garlic{3%cloves}. Thinly slice @scallions{2}(separating whites from greens). Peel and dice @carrots{6%ounce} into ¼-inch pieces. Dice @celery{2.5%ounce} into ¼-inch pieces.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{2%teaspoon} in a #large pot{} over medium-high heat. Add @Italian chicken sausage mix{9%ounce} and cook, breaking up meat into pieces, until browned and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}. Turn off heat; transfer sausage to a #plate{}. Wipe out pot.

In a large pot, heat a drizzle of oil over medium-high heat. Add garlic and scallion whites; cook, stirring, until fragrant, ~{1-2%minutes}. Add carrots and celery; season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Cook, stirring, until softened, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Stir in @tomato paste{1%unit}, @crushed tomatoes{13.76%ounce}, @cannellini beans{1%can} and their liquid, @veggie stock concentrate{2%unit}, @water{2%cups}, a pinch of @chili flakes{1%teaspoon}, salt, and pepper. Bring to a boil, then reduce heat to medium. Cook, scraping any browned bits from bottom of pot, until flavors meld, ~{6-8%minutes}.

> Use pot used for sausage here.

Add @Israeli couscous{2.5%ounce} to soup; season with salt and pepper. Cook, stirring occasionally, until couscous is tender and soup has thickened slightly, ~{6-8%minutes}.

Meanwhile, in a #medium pan{}, heat a drizzle of @olive oil{1%teaspoon} over medium heat. Add @panko breadcrumbs{1/4%cup} and a pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{}; cook, stirring, until lightly browned, ~{3-5%minutes}.

> TIP: Watch carefully to avoid burning.

Once soup is done, stir in cooked sausage.

Divide soup between bowls. Top with @Parmesan cheese{3%tablespoon}(@grated), toasted panko, scallion greens, and a pinch of pepper to taste. Serve.

> Chicken Sausage is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 165°.